Oui. Le settings.json est déjà dans ton Dockerfile :
Dockerfile
COPY settings.json /tmp/settings.json
cp /tmp/settings.json /home/coder/.local/share/code-server/User/settings.json
Sans modifier l’image, fais-le via Helm avec un ConfigMap monté sur ce fichier.
Ajoute un template :
apiVersion: v1
kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: code-server-settings
data:
  settings.json: |
    {
      "terminal.integrated.defaultProfile.linux": "restricted",
      "terminal.integrated.profiles.linux": {
        "restricted": {
          "path": "/bin/bash",
          "args": ["--noprofile", "--norc"]
        }
      },
      "terminal.integrated.env.linux": {
        "PATH": "/opt/blocked-bin:/usr/lib/code-server/lib/vscode/bin/remote-cli:/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin"
      }
    }
YAML
Et dans values.yaml :
YAML
extraConfigmapMounts:
  - name: blocked-commands
    mountPath: /opt/blocked-bin
    configMap: blocked-commands
    defaultMode: 0555
    readOnly: true

  - name: code-server-settings
    mountPath: /home/coder/.local/share/code-server/User/settings.json
    subPath: settings.json
    configMap: code-server-settings
    defaultMode: 0444
    readOnly: true
